Rafe tensed. Matthis clenched his jaw. The skeletons did not stumble or wander. Shoulder to shoulder, they stepped around Matthis and Rafe. Rafe exhaled. Matthis narrowed his eyes.

Each deliberate step touched the mud without a squelch and lifted again without a stain. Pristine, white bones drifted through the square. A group of children playing a game in an alley. Their leather ball fell. Their faces turned pale. They scurried away like roaches from light and peeked around corners and through door cracks. The skeletons did not stop or react. Empty sockets forward, they proceeded one step after another. The street echoed Matthis's and Rafe's footsteps. 

One man in a dusty black cap emerged onto a narrow street with his pickaxe slung behind his neck, the flat end curled around his shoulder and tucked safely into his armpit. In a single file, the skeletons drifted around him. The man jumped and swung his axe into one of the skeletons in one fluid motion, dropped the haft, and stumbled backward into a wall, his thick hands in fists. Rafe laid a hand on his shoulder. The skeleton he had struck lay in a scattered pile of bone fragments. The others did not break stride. The fragments reassembled themselves in a way Matthis never had witnessed before. Pieces flew through the air and reattached without a crack or seam anywhere, and a complete skeleton resumed its silent march as though nothing had happened. Rafe and Matthis looked at each other. The man, his mouth open, pulled his pickaxe out of the mud and stared after them.

The skeletons tread around a corner and glided past the carpenter's shop. Through a window, Matthis spotted Mercy and the carpenter's wife. Mercy halted mid sentence. Her eyebrows rose and she bared her teeth. She rushed to the shop door and flung it open. Rafe glanced behind him. Over fifty yards behind, Mercy stalked them, her eyes shadowed. She whispered to people who emerged out of doors and appeared confused. A group slowly formed around her. Every face in her group set their faces into hard lines. Many carried pickaxes, ready for use. 

Heads ducked out of windows and doors, and then slammed shut. A woman with a baby in her arms squeaked and rushed to cover her child with her body and scramble around a corner. Three men outside the apothecary fell to their knees. A man in a pristine white robe, whom Matthis had never seen, sat atop a sleek, muscular horse and spoke to Bartholomew and Godric. The man's head snapped forward and watched the procession, arms folded and resting on the horse's neck, face hard. Bartholomew gaped, and his arms circled his middle. Godric steadied himself on a wall.

Nine skeletons crested the cemetery hill, followed by Matthis and Rafe. A group trailed behind them, headed by Mercy.